05193nam a22006975i 9781487583804DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191976onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875838047 a10.3138/97814875838042doi  a(DE-B1597)527985  a(OCoLC)1129178911  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aHIS0160002bisacsh1 aShortt, S.E.D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Search for an Ideal :bSix Canadian Intellectuals and their Convictions in an Age of Transition 1890–1930 /cS.E.D. Shortt. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1976  a1 online resource (228 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tTHE SEARCH FOR AN IDEAL -- t1. Introduction: 'A Search for an Ideal' -- t2. The Ideal in Nature -- t3. Romantic Idealist -- t4. The Ideal in Culture -- t5. Classical-Christian Idealist -- t6. The Emergence of the Social Scientist -- t7. The Empirical Ideal -- t8. Conclusion: Conviction in an Age of Transition -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithin the context of the debate between idealism and empiricism, this book studies the ideas of six representative Canadian intellectuals of the late Victorian era. These six were chosen primarily because of their ideas on contemporary social questions -- views which may cast disconcerting light on certain aspects of present-day Canadian society. All were academics, and shared a common recognition of social issues and a similar self-image, yet they were hardly a homogenous group: they were individuals who expressed their own unique attitudes rather than a collective viewpoint. Sir Andrew Macphail, professor of the history of medicine at McGill, was fascinated by the social implications of evolutionary naturalism. For Archibald MacMechan, professor of English at Dalhousie, British authors of the nineteenth century provided a romantic idealism that accurately defined man's place in the universe. Another professor English, James Cappon of Queen's, built much of his thought, whether on imperialism or on literature, around a concept of culture similar to that of Matthew Arnold. Plato tempered with Christianity appeared to be a reliable philosophical guide to Maurice Hutton, professor of classics at the University of Toronto. Political economist Adam Shortt of Queen's University found much to admire in the ideas of John Stuart Mill; his counterpart at Toronto, James Mavor, borrowed many of his attitudes from British and French positivism. Each man is the subject of a chapter constituting of three parts: a biographical section, a consideration of the essential core of his belief -- his view of man, God, and the universe -- and an examination of how his background and philosophy fround express in his ideas about culture and society. No attempt is made to document the influence of the ideas of these academics for, as they themselves asserted, they were essentially moralists, not men of action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aHISTORY / Historiography.2bisacsh1 aCappon, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutton, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacMechan, Archibald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacphail, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMavor, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShortt, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Pac